{
    "id": "383",
    "title": "National Early Warning Score (NEWS)",
    "desc": "The National Early Warning Score (NEWS) determines the degree of illness of a patient using six physiological findings and one observation.",
    "data": {
        "orgreference": [
            {
                "href": "https://www.rcplondon.ac.uk/sites/default/files/documents/national-early-warning-score-standardising-assessment-acute-illness-severity-nhs.pdf",
                "text": "Royal College of Physicians. National Early Warning Score (NEWS) Standardising the assessment of acute-illness severity in the NHS. Report of a working party. London: RCP, 2012."
            }
        ],
        "other_refer": [
            {
                "href": "https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20637974",
                "text": "Prytherch D, Smith GB, Schmidt PE, Featherstone PI. ViEWS – towards a national Early Warning Score for detecting adult inpatient deterioration. Resuscitation 2010;81:932–7."
            }
        ],
        "evidence": "<p>Addition of the selected points; points assigned below:</p>",
        "facts": "<p>See formula table, below.</p>\n<table class=\"table table-bordered table-hover\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Criteria</th>\n<th>Point Value</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"2\"><strong>Respiratory Rate (breaths per minute)</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&le;8</td>\n<td>3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9-11</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>12-20</td>\n<td>0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>21-24</td>\n<td>2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&ge;25</td>\n<td>3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"2\"><strong>Oxygen Saturation (%)</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&le;91</td>\n<td>3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>92-93</td>\n<td>2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>94-95</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&ge;96</td>\n<td>0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"2\"><strong>Any Supplemental Oxygen</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Yes</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>No</td>\n<td>0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"2\"><strong>Temperature in &deg;C (&deg;F)</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&le;35.0 (95)</td>\n<td>3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>35.1-36.0 (95.1-96.8)</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>36.1-38.0 (96.9-100.4)</td>\n<td>0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>38.1-39.0 (100.5-102.2)</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&ge;39.1 (&ge;102.3)</td>\n<td>2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"2\"><strong>Systolic BP</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&le;90</td>\n<td>3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>91-100</td>\n<td>2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>101-110</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>111-219</td>\n<td>0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&ge;220</td>\n<td>3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"2\"><strong>Heart Rate (beats per minute)</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&le;40</td>\n<td>3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>41-50</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>51-90</td>\n<td>0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>91-110</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>111-130</td>\n<td>2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&ge;131</td>\n<td>3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"2\"><strong><abbr title=\"Alert, Voice, Pain, Unresponsive\">AVPU</abbr></strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>A</td>\n<td>0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>V, P, or U</td>\n<td>3</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><strong>Interpretation</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>A low score (NEWS 1&ndash;4) should prompt assessment by a competent registered nurse who should decide if a change to frequency of clinical monitoring or an escalation of clinical care is required.</li>\n<li>A medium score (ie NEWS of 5&ndash;6 or a RED score) should prompt an urgent review by a clinician skilled with competencies in the assessment of acute illness &ndash; usually a ward-based doctor or acute team nurse, who should consider whether escalation of care to a team with critical-care skills is required (ie critical care outreach team).\n<ul>\n<li>A RED score refers to an extreme variation in a single physiological parameter (i.e., a score of 3 on the NEWS chart in any one physiological parameter, colored RED to aid identification; e.g., heart rate</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>A high score (NEWS &ge;7) should prompt emergency assessment by a clinical team/critical care outreach team with critical-care competencies and usually transfer of the patient to a higher dependency care area.</li>\n</ul>",
